    month = feb,
   volume = 764,
      eid = {134},
    pages = {134},
 abstract = "{We explore non-thermal emission from a shocked interstellar medium,
which is identified as an expanding shell, driven by a relativistic jet
in active galactic nuclei (AGNs). In this work, we particularly focus on
parsec-scale size mini shells surrounding mini radio lobes. From the
radio to X-ray band, the mini radio lobe emission dominates the faint
emission from the mini shell. On the other hand, we find that
inverse-Compton (IC) emission from the shell can overwhelm the
associated lobe emission at the very high energy (VHE; E {\gt} 100 GeV)
{$\gamma$}-ray range, because energy densities of synchrotron photons from
the lobe and/or soft photons from the AGN nucleus are large and IC
scattering works effectively. The predicted IC emission from nearby mini
shells can be detected with the Cherenkov Telescope Array and they are
potentially a new class of VHE {$\gamma$}-ray emitters.
}",
